{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"608c541f-ece9-4cb4-b66e-865ab5d6f986","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_018EHYtTcuguphAxjPybtmX3","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Migrating xUnit v2 to v3"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01DcsWLCJzShZVrYNaQihgLK","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"dotnet --list-sdks 2>/dev/null | tail -5","description":"Check available .NET SDKs","initial_wait":10},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Check available .NET SDKs"}],"interactionId":"ba0b7b76-ec03-49a0-879c-9e0a8b243e0e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I understand the project. Let me migrate from xUnit.net v2 to v3. The key changes are:\n\n1. **Target framework**: xUnit v3 requires at least `net472` (or a modern .NET like `net6.0`+). `net462` is not supported. I'll upgrade to `net472` to stay on .NET Framework, or better yet, let me check what xUnit v3 supports. Actually, xUnit v3 requires `net472` as the minimum for .NET Framework, or `net6.0`+ for modern .NET.\n\n2. **Package references**: \n   - Replace `xunit` v2 with `xunit.v3`\n   - For the test runner, xUnit v3 defaults to `Microsoft.Testing.Platform`, though `xunit.runner.visualstudio` v3 is also available as an alternative\n   - `Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk` may still be needed depending on the runner choice\n\nActually, I need to reconsider how xUnit v3 fundamentally works. The test project itself becomes an executable rather than a library, so the project file needs `OutputType` set to `Exe` and only requires the `xunit.v3` package reference. The test runner is built directly into the compiled assembly, eliminating the need for `Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk` or the separate runner packages.\n\nHowever, for `dotnet test` to work properly with v3, you'll need the v3 version of `xunit.runner.visualstudio` to bridge the gap between the executable test project and the test infrastructure.\n\nThe cleanest path forward is to bump the target framework to `net472`, swap out the xUnit v2 packages for `xunit.v3`, remove the test SDK dependency since the project becomes self-contained, and add the `OutputType` set to `Exe` so it can run as a standalone executable.\n\nFor the actual test code, the namespaces and attributes like `[Fact]` and `Assert.True` remain unchanged, though I should verify if there are any behavioral differences in the assertions themselves. The main consideration is updating the test runner configuration—xUnit v3 has a built-in runner that works with `dotnet test`, so I may need to adjust or remove the VSTest runner settings in `global.json` to ensure compatibility.\n\nNow I'm checking the latest xUnit v3 package versions and compatibility requirements. The minimum .NET Framework version for xUnit v3 is `net472`, not `net462`, so I'll need to update the target framework. I'm planning the migration steps: updating the project file to use the newer TFM, adding the executable output type, and replacing the package references with the xUnit v3 packages.\n\nFor the test file itself, the code should remain compatible since xUnit v3 maintains the same `Xunit` namespace for the core attributes and assertions. I'm also reconsidering the global.json configuration—xUnit v3 works with Microsoft.Testing.Platform as the recommended runner, though it can also work with VSTest if the appropriate adapter is included.\n\nThe cleanest approach for xUnit v3 is to have the test project run as an executable using Microsoft.Testing.Platform natively, which means updating global.json to specify `\"runner\": \"Microsoft.Testing.Platform\"`. I believe the `xunit.v3` package includes everything needed for this integration out of the box. Let me proceed with the migration and verify it builds and runs correctly.","outputTokens":1840,"requestId":"3439:2A41E8:15E0369:173E994:6A045FCF"},"id":"4c4ec6c3-051c-4029-b12b-e5950bdc14cb","timestamp":"2026-05-13T11:26:41.488Z","parentId":"729ab186-5a34-40cc-a81e-8695b9613035"}
